{"reasoning":"Both descriptions talk about a prone wrestler whose body behaves incorrectly during an animation.  
Ground truth key points: (1) wrestler is on the ground, (2) the hand penetrates the body (clipping), (3) the whole body shakes rapidly.  
Generated report key points: (1) wrestler is on the ground recovering after a match, (2) torso and limbs twist/contort violently (an implicit form of rapid shaking / instability), (3) occurs during a transition animation.  
Although the generated report does not explicitly use the word “clipping,” violent twisting/contorting implies self-intersection and the same sort of physics/animation instability noted in the ground truth. No conflicting details are present. Therefore both texts refer to the same underlying bug of a wrestler model exhibiting rapid, unstable motion and self-penetration while on the ground.","match":true}

Because the distinctive rotor-stopped-but-hovering behavior (and the oscillation) is absent from the generated report, the two reports do not describe the same bug.","match":false}
